full_text: @Meg9Time Wait they aren't?
@david_perell This is a sobering thought for me.

@danctheduck Interesting insight. I'd also add that passively consuming social interaction is akin to watching all of your close friends hang out at the mall from a distance - you feel fleeting gratification and long-term depression.

@icecrmsocialist Two most important things I think are to stick to a budget and surround yourself with friends that believe in you. I can't imagine being where I am now without both. Budget ensures positive financial trajectory, friends ensure positive community trajectory üòÄ

@icecrmsocialist As far as rent - yeah that can be a killer. I usually recommend no more than 35% of income on rent. Having a roommate helped when I lived in expensive areas. This cost of living index was really helpful for figuring out where to live next https://t.co/8cUK31Fmgk

@icecrmsocialist Thank you! Actually as it turned out, buying a home had a negligible effect (forgot to mention HOA fees @ $300 brought housing costs to $800 / mo). Had I not borrowed money and just put my savings into debt payments vs. house, I'd have paid it off at about the same rate.
@icecrmsocialist @jenniferm_q Now: $100k+ with salary/bonus/benefits/stock. $1.2k rent in downtown Richmond, VA. Mostly single income now because we are expecting soon :)

@icecrmsocialist @jenniferm_q End of debt (2017) - combined salary ~$87k, side work ~$5. Same mortgage payments. Sold place to move for work, used that to pay off remainder of debt! Estimated ~$33k / year towards debt. Now that goes directly into investments. Standard of living only slightly increased.

@icecrmsocialist @jenniferm_q Sidenote - pre-buying place/marriage, 2013 - $45k salary, Orlando. Lived w/ roommate, split $1.6k rent Orlando. Saved $1k / mo for ~2 years combined with family gift for wedding to buy place. $96k @ $24k down, Included family loan in debt.

@icecrmsocialist @jenniferm_q Sure! Off top of my head (numbers may be slightly off):
In 2014: wife & my combined debt: ~$135k (~$120k student loans, ~$6k car loan, ~$10k family loan). Combined income: ~$75k before taxes. Mortgage: ~$500 / mo in Orlando, FL (bought place before married).
@AdamKarb @jenniferm_q @DaveRamsey üòÇü§£üòÅ

@aeroeng11 @jenniferm_q Right on. Same situation here, fortunately had an awesome wife to take on financial woes with. Didn't earn much combined early on, so lived by a modest & very precise budget.

Safety net savings def helped us also. Acted as great buffer between having emergencies & going broke :)

@jenniferm_q If anyone here is struggling and losing hope, I'd be happy to help you budget. I've done so before with many folks to a positive outcome. It will get better, but you've gotta make the math work.
